\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 16. E. scoparia} L.,{\i  Sp.Pl.} 353 (1753). Slender, erect shrub 1-6 m; young twigs glabrous or puberulent. Leaves 4-7 mm, in whorls of 3-4, linear, erecto-patent, glabrous; margins revolute, concealing about 2/3 of lower surface. Flowers in narrow, often interrupted, terminal racemes, sometimes grouped into lax panicles; pedicels 2 mm, glabrous, with 3 bracteoles near the middle. Sepals 0·5-1·5 mm, ovate, glabrous; corolla 1·5-3 mm, green, variably tinged with red, broadly campanulate, with erect, deltate lobes about as long as the tube; anthers included, without appendages. Ovary glabrous; stigma conspicuously capitate, reddish-purple. {\i Woods and heaths; calcifuge. S. W. Europe, extending eastwards to W.C. Italy and northwards to N.C. France}. Az Bl Co Ga Hs It Lu Sa [Ho].
