\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. B. spiculifolia} (Salisb.) Reichenb.,{\i  Fl. Germ. Excurs.} 414 (1831). Dwarf shrub with ascending stems 10-15 cm; young twigs puberulent. Leaves 4-5 mm, crowded, in rather irregular whorls of 4-5, linear-oblong, minutely ciliate and often with a stout, terminal, gland-tipped hair; margins revolute, leaving 1/4-1/3 of the lower surface exposed. Flowers 4-merous, in dense, shortly cylindrical or globose, terminal racemes; pedicels 2-3 mm. Calyx 1·5 mm, with broadly deltate lobes scarcely as long as the tube, pink; corolla 3 mm, campanulate, with ovate lobes about as long as the tube, bright reddish-pink. Anthers included, without appendages. Ovary and capsule glabrous.{\i  Woods and subalpine pastures; calcifuge. Mountains of Romania and of the Balkan peninsula, southwards to N. Greece.} ?Al Bu Gr Ju Rm.
